---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="phone is cigarette for the brain — hkg">
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-white"
      >
        phone is cigarette for the brain
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-neutral-500">A manifesto, of sorts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-6 text-base text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        I need to tell you something and I'm going to say it plainly: your phone
        is making you worse at being a person.
      </p>
      <p>
        Not because technology is evil. Not because the internet is a wasteland.
        But because the specific way most people use their phones — constantly,
        compulsively, reflexively — is degrading something important in them.
        The capacity for sustained attention. The tolerance for boredom. The
        ability to be fully present in a room with another human being.
      </p>
      <p>
        We've all seen it. The dinner table where everyone is looking at their
        phones. The walk where someone can't go two minutes without checking
        something. The meeting where people are half-present at best. We see it
        in others and we judge it, and then we go and do exactly the same thing.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white pt-4">
        What you're actually losing
      </h2>

      <p>
        Boredom is not a bug. It's a feature. When you're bored, your brain
        doesn't go offline — it goes into a mode called the Default Mode
        Network, which is associated with creativity, memory consolidation,
        empathy, and self-reflection. This is when you have ideas. This is when
        you make sense of your experiences. This is when you figure out how you
        actually feel about things.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every time you reach for your phone to fill a moment of silence, you're
        interrupting that process. You're not just wasting time. You're actively
        preventing the kind of thinking that makes you more creative, more
        emotionally intelligent, and more interesting to be around.
      </p>
      <p>
        Meanwhile, the platforms themselves are designed by armies of very smart
        people whose full-time job is to make the app as difficult to put down
        as possible. You are not weak. You are up against something engineered
        specifically to exploit the way your brain works. But that doesn't mean
        you can't fight back.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white pt-4">
        What I actually suggest
      </h2>

      <p>
        I'm not telling you to delete everything and move to a cabin. I'm asking
        you to try some things and see how they feel.
      </p>

      <ul class="space-y-2.5 pl-2">
        {
          [
            "No phone for the first 30 minutes after waking up. Seriously. Not even a quick check. Just those 30 minutes, every day.",
            "No phone at dinner. Put it face-down across the room. Have the conversation.",
            "When you're waiting for something — in a queue, at a light, for a friend — just wait. Don't fill it. Let the thought come.",
            "When you're walking somewhere, don't listen to anything sometimes. Just walk and think.",
            "Charge your phone outside your bedroom. Buy an alarm clock. Sleep better.",
            "Delete the apps you open out of habit, not out of intention. If you're opening it 40 times a day without meaning to, delete it.",
            "Designate phone-free times. Mine is after 9pm. It's not always perfect but it's mostly maintained.",
          ].map((item) => (
            <li class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-neutral-600" />
              <span>{item}</span>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white pt-4">The harder argument</h2>

      <p>
        There's a version of this argument that goes: the phone is just a tool,
        and tools aren't the problem, it's how you use them. This is true and
        also slightly dishonest, because these particular tools are designed with
        the explicit goal of maximizing the time you spend using them. They are
        not neutral.
      </p>
      <p>
        The people who built them know this. Many of them don't let their own
        children use the products. That should tell you something.
      </p>
      <p>
        I'm not asking you to be perfect. I'm asking you to be a little more
        intentional about something that's quietly consuming enormous portions of
        your life and attention, and whether the exchange is actually worth it.
      </p>
      <p>Most of us, if we're honest, would say it isn't.</p>

      <div class="mt-8 rounded-xl bg-white p-6 text-neutral-900 font-medium">
        Put the phone down. Look up. Something interesting is probably happening
        right in front of you.
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
